In [[Irish language|Irish]] '''Ollam''' or '''Ollamh''' (anglicised '''Ollave''' or '''Ollav'''), is a master in a particular trade or skill. In early [[Irish Literature]] it generally refers to the highest rank of [[Fili]]. In modern Irish it means "[[professor]]".


[[Ollamh Fodhla]], meaning "great teacher," was used to designate various prominent men throughout history.

*  The most distinguished Ollamh is said to have been also a king of Ireland and eighteenth in descent from Eremon, son of Milesius. 


